{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-post-js","path":"/blog/scss-in-angular-cli-6","webpackCompilationHash":"","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>If you’re familiar working with SCSS in Angular CLI 1.x before and now you’re wondering how to use it in version 6, a brand new version that comes with Angular 6, I’m here to help.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 1000px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 41.66666666666667%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Sass logo\"\n        title=\"The Sass logo\"\n        src=\"/static/f24335a00696d1c6b03d7826cdc48942/5d442/sass-image.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f24335a00696d1c6b03d7826cdc48942/f13e0/sass-image.png 250w,\n/static/f24335a00696d1c6b03d7826cdc48942/87981/sass-image.png 500w,\n/static/f24335a00696d1c6b03d7826cdc48942/5d442/sass-image.png 1000w,\n/static/f24335a00696d1c6b03d7826cdc48942/a1b30/sass-image.png 1200w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The Sass logo</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>This is how the style config in the CLI v1.x looks like in .angular-cli.json file.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">&quot;defaults&quot;: {\n  &quot;styleExt&quot;: &quot;scss&quot;,\n  &quot;component&quot;: {}\n}</code></pre></div>\n<p>But if you take a look into a config schema of <strong>angular.json</strong> file in version 6, you will no longer find this config anymore. But don’t worry, Angular CLI team got it cover in much easier way. To use SCSS, simply import you scss files (the default value is <code class=\"language-text\">src/styles.scss</code>) in your project level in an <strong>angular.json</strong> file like this.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">{\n  ...\n  projects: {\n    [your_project_name]: {\n      ...\n      architect: {\n        build: {\n          ...\n          options: {\n            styles:{\n              &quot;src/styles.scss&quot;\n            }\n          }\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}</code></pre></div>\n<p>That’s it, you’re good to go with SCSS! No any other config needed because CLI team just got it covered so you don’t have to tell the config which CSS-preprocessor is gonna be used anymore. By dig deeper in their build script (<code class=\"language-text\">node_modules/@angular-devkit/build-angular/src/angular-cli-files/models/webpack-configs/styles.js</code>), I’m pretty sure that you can include any type of <em>.css</em>, <em>.sass</em>, <em>.scss</em>, <em>.less</em> or <em>.styl (stylus)</em> and start your CSS coding right away. I’ve tried it, very easy!</p>\n<p>Plus, they also provide the way to config target browsers for autoprefixer easily. You can find a file name browserslist in src folder and change the target browsers for your autoprefixer. I haven’t tried that yet, let me know your result if you already tried it.</p>\n<p>This is just an example of a post. The original is here: <a href=\"https://medium.com/@vissanu_s/quick-tip-how-to-use-scss-in-angular-cli-6-63d263b3481c\">https://medium.com/@vissanu_s/quick-tip-how-to-use-scss-in-angular-cli-6-63d263b3481c</a></p>","timeToRead":1,"frontmatter":{"title":"Quick Tip: How to use SCSS in Angular CLI 6","date":"21 Dec 2018","tags":["javascript","angular","sass"],"path":"blog/scss-in-angular-cli-6","excerpt":"Configure SCSS for your next Angular proje